          "body": "The chapter's only woe-oracle (10:16) and beatitude (10:17) place national welfare squarely on the character of its leadership. The woe is over a land whose king is a 'lad' (naar — not necessarily young in years but immature in judgment and character) and whose princes feast in the morning. Morning feasting is not merely indulgent; it is sequentially disordered — pleasure before duty, self-gratification before the work of governance. The blessed land has a king 'of nobility' (ben chorim — son of free men, a phrase carrying both genealogical dignity and the moral formation that comes with it) whose princes eat at the appropriate time, for strength rather than drunkenness. The contrast is not between abstinence and feasting but between self-discipline and self-indulgence in the exercise of power. Verse 18 draws the architectural consequence: through indolence the rafters sag, through slack hands the house leaks. The image is both literal and political — the nation whose leadership refuses to do the hard, daily work of governance wakes up one morning to a roof that has been quietly collapsing for years. Calvin noted in his commentary on this passage that rulers who give themselves to pleasure while the commonwealth deteriorates are not merely negligent but culpable before God."
